# Tailwind State and Accessibility

- Interactive components must have visible `focus-visible` styles.
- Prefer ring-based focus over removing outlines.
- Disabled states should be explicit:
  - `disabled:opacity-50 disabled:pointer-events-none`
- Prefer `aria-*` and `data-*` variants for state-driven styling (especially Radix/Shadcn patterns).
- Do not hide information needed by assistive technology.

## Cursor affordance

- Every clickable gets `cursor-pointer`: buttons, links, custom clickables (`div`/`span` with `onClick`), menu items, tabs, toggles, sortable headers, clickable rows/cards.
- **Tailwind v4 Preflight sets `<button>` to `cursor: default`** — the browser no longer shows a pointer on buttons. Add `cursor-pointer` explicitly on every button/clickable, or restore it once in the base layer: `@layer base { button:not(:disabled), [role="button"]:not([aria-disabled="true"]) { cursor: pointer } }`. This is the usual cause of "no pointer cursor on anything."
- Disabled controls use `cursor-not-allowed` (with `disabled:pointer-events-none`), never `cursor-pointer`.
- Match other affordances to the action: `cursor-text`, `cursor-grab`/`cursor-grabbing`, `cursor-col-resize`, `cursor-wait`.

## Full state set

- Every interactive element ships `hover`, `focus-visible`, `active`, and `disabled` — not just the resting style.
- Add a short `transition` (e.g. `transition-colors`) so state changes aren't jarring.
- Async triggers disable themselves and show a pending state (spinner/skeleton) to block double-submit.
- Keep hit areas ≥ 44×44px on interactive controls.
- Non-native clickables need `role`, `tabIndex={0}`, and Enter/Space handlers — then all the states above still apply.

## Most-missed clickables (audit by name)

Repeatedly shipped without `cursor-pointer`/states — check each explicitly:

- Icon-only buttons (close `×`, kebab `⋮`, chevrons, FABs).
- Dropdown / select / combobox triggers (a `<button>` or `<div>` opening a listbox).
- Tabs, segmented controls, toggles, switches, chips, pills.
- Clickable table rows, sortable column headers, pagination controls.
- Cards / list items that navigate on click; avatars/badges that open menus.
- Accordion headers, disclosure triangles, breadcrumb links.

## Self-check before delivering UI

Do not call a UI done until, element by element:

1. Every clickable has `cursor-pointer` (disabled → `cursor-not-allowed` + handler actually blocked).
2. `hover`, `focus-visible`, `active`, and `disabled` are all styled — not just the resting state.
3. A keyboard user can reach and operate it (visible focus ring; Enter/Space on non-native clickables).
4. Async triggers disable + show a pending state (no double-submit).

If you cannot point to where each of these is implemented for a control, it is not done.
